### Cloning Telescope

The first step will be getting Telescope to run on your local machine. To do so, we'll need to first download its code. 

Telescope's code is stored on [GitHub](http://github.com/TelescopeJS/Telescope), so we'll use the [Git](http://git-scm.com/) version control system to get it.

If you're on Mac OS, you can use the very good (and free) [GitHub Mac](https://mac.github.com/) app. 

Or, you can simply [install Git separately](http://git-scm.com/downloads) and then run the following command from your terminal:

```
git clone git@github.com:TelescopeJS/Telescope.git
```

or

```
git clone https://github.com/TelescopeJS/Telescope.git
```

Which should create a directory called `Telescope`. 

### Installing Meteor

The next step will be installing [Meteor](https://www.meteor.com/), the framework on which Telescope is based. 

To install it, open a terminal window and type:

```
curl https://install.meteor.com/ | sh
```

### Running Telescope

We're now finally ready to run Telescope. In your terminal, access the Telescope repository with

```
cd Telescope
```

(Replacing "Telescope" with the appopriate path).

Then run your app with:

```
meteor
```

If everything worked, you should see the following message:

```
=> App running at: http://localhost:3000/
```

Congratulations! You now have an instance of Telescope running locally at [http://localhost:3000/](http://localhost:3000/).
